[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] Mongoose is a MongoDB object modeling tool designed to work in an asynchronous environment.
[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] Mongoose supports Node.js and Deno (alpha).
[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] The official documentation website is mongoosejs.com.
[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] Mongoose 9.0.0 was released on November 21, 2025.
[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] You can find more details on backwards breaking changes in 9.0.0 on our docs site.
[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] Check out the plugins search site to see hundreds of related modules from the community.
[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] Next, learn how to write your own plugin from the docs or this blog post.
[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] Please base pull requests against the `master` branch and follow the contributing guide.
[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] If your pull requests makes documentation changes, please do **not** modify any `.html` files.
[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] The `.html` files are compiled code, so please make your changes in `docs/*.pug`, `lib/*.js`, or `test/docs/*.js`.
[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] Mongoose 6.8.0 also includes alpha support for Deno.
[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] Or, using Deno's `createRequire()` for CommonJS support as follows.
[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] You can then run the above script using the following.
[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] Mongoose Studio is a free, fully open-source, browser-based MongoDB GUI built by the Mongoose team for apps that already use Mongoose.
[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] The maintainers of mongoose and thousands of other packages are working with Tidelift to deliver commercial support and maintenance for the open source dependencies you use to build your applications.
[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] Save time, reduce risk, and improve code health, while paying the maintainers of the exact dependencies you use.
[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] If your app uses only one database, you should use `mongoose.connect`.
[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] If you need to create additional connections, use `mongoose.createConnection`.
[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] Both `connect` and `createConnection` take a `mongodb://` URI, or the parameters `host, database, port, options`.
[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] Once connected, the `open` event is fired on the `Connection` instance.
[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] If you're using `mongoose.connect`, the `Connection` is `mongoose.connection`.
[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] Otherwise, `mongoose.createConnection` return value is a `Connection`.
[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] Models are defined through the `Schema` interface.
[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] The first argument is the *singular* name of the collection your model is for.
[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] Then `MyModel` will use the **tickets** collection, not the **ticket** collection.
[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] You can also `findOne`, `findById`, `update`, etc.
[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] Where `Comment` is a `Schema` we created.
[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] Embedded documents enjoy all the same features as your models.
[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] You can intercept method arguments via middleware.
[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] Moreover, you can mutate the incoming `method` arguments so that subsequent middleware see different values for those arguments.
[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] `type`, when used in a schema has special meaning within Mongoose.
[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] Mongoose is built on top of the official MongoDB Node.js driver.
[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] Each mongoose model keeps a reference to a native MongoDB driver collection.
[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] The collection object can be accessed using `YourModel.collection`.
[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] However, using the collection object directly bypasses all mongoose features, including hooks, validation, etc.
[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] The one notable exception that `YourModel.collection` still buffers commands.
[src:mongoose-odm/automattic-mongoose] As such, `YourModel.collection.find()` will **not** return a cursor.
