[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] A **document-oriented database**, or **document store**, is a computer program and data storage system designed for storing, retrieving, and managing document-oriented information, also known as semi-structured data.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] Document-oriented databases are one of the main categories of NoSQL databases, and the popularity of the term "document-oriented database" has grown alongside the adoption of NoSQL itself.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] XML databases are a subclass of document-oriented databases optimized for XML documents.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] Graph databases are similar, but add another layer, the *relationship*, which allows them to link documents for rapid traversal.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] Document-oriented databases are conceptually an extension of the key–value store, another type of NoSQL database.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] In key-value stores, data is treated as opaque by the database, whereas document-oriented systems exploit the internal structure of documents to extract metadata and optimize storage and queries.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] Although in practice the distinction can be minimal due to modern tooling, document stores are designed to provide a richer programming experience with modern programming techniques.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] Document databases differ significantly from traditional relational databases (RDBs).
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] Relational databases store data in predefined tables, often requiring an object to be split across multiple tables.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] In contrast, document databases store all information for a given object in a single document, with each document potentially having a unique structure.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] This design eliminates the need for object-relational mapping when loading data into the database.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] The central concept of a document-oriented database is the notion of a *document*.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] Although implementations vary in their specific definitions, document-oriented databases generally treat documents as self-contained units that encapsulate and encode data in a standardized format.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] Common encoding formats include XML, YAML, JSON, as well as binary representations such as BSON.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] Documents in a document store are equivalent to the programming concept of an object.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] They are not required to adhere to a fixed schema, and documents within the same collection may contain different fields or structures.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] Fields may be optional, and documents of the same logical type may differ in composition.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] The two example documents share some structural elements but also contain unique fields.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] The structure, text, and other data within each document are collectively referred to as the document's content and can be accessed or modified using retrieval or editing operations.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] Unlike relational databases, in which each record contains the same fields and unused fields are left empty, document-oriented databases do not require uniform fields across documents.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] This design allows new information to be added to some documents without affecting the structure of others.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] Document databases often support the storage of additional metadata alongside the document content.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] Such metadata may relate to organizational features, security, indexing, or other implementation-specific features.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] The core operations supported by a document-oriented database for manipulating documents are similar to those in other databases.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] Although terminology is not perfectly standardized, these operations are generally recognized as Create, Read, Update, and Delete (CRUD).
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] Documents in a document-oriented database are addressed via a unique identifier.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] This identifier, often a string, URI, or path, can be used to retrieve the document from the database.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] Most document stores maintain an index on the key to optimize retrieval, and in some implementations the key is required when creating or inserting a new document.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] In addition to key-based access, document-oriented databases typically provide an API or query language that enables retrieval based on document content or associated metadata.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] For example, a query may return all documents with a specific field matching a given value.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] The available query features, indexing options, and performance characteristics vary across implementations.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] Document stores differ from key-value stores in that they exploit the internal structure and metadata of stored documents.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] In many key-value stores, values are treated as opaque or "black-box" data, meaning the database system does not interpret their internal structure.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] By contrast, document-oriented databases can classify and interpret document content.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] Document databases typically provide mechanisms for updating or editing the content or metadata of a document.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] Updates may involve replacing the entire document or modifying individual elements or fields within the document.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] These organizational structures may differ between logical and physical representations (e.g. on disk or in memory).
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] A document-oriented database can be viewed as a specialized form of key-value store, which is itself a category of NoSQL database.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] In a basic key-value store, the stored value is typically treated as opaque by the database system.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] By contrast, a document-oriented database provides APIs or a query and update language that allows queries and modifications based on the internal structure of the document.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] For users who do not require advanced query, retrieval, or update capabilities, the distinction between document-oriented databases and key-value stores may be minimal.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] Some search engine and information retrieval systems, such as Apache Solr and Elasticsearch, provide document storage and support core document operations.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] As a result, they may meet certain functional definitions of a document-oriented database, although their primary design goals differ.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] In a relational database, data is organized into predefined types represented as tables.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] Each table contains rows (records) with a fixed set of columns (fields), so all records in a table share the same structure.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] Administrators typically define indexes on selected fields to improve query performance.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] A central principle of relational database design is database normalization, in which data that might otherwise be repeated is stored in separate tables and linked using keys.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] When records in different tables are related, a foreign key is used to associate them.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] For example, an address book application may store a contact's name, image, phone numbers, mailing addresses, and email addresses.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] In a normalized relational design, separate tables might be created for contacts, phone numbers, and email addresses.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] The phone number table would include a foreign key referencing the associated contact.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] To reconstruct a complete contact record, the database retrieves related information from each table using the foreign keys and combines it into a single record.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] In contrast, a document-oriented database stores all data related to an object within a single document, and stored in the database as a single entry.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] In the address book example,the contact's name, image, and contact information may be stored together in one document.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] The document is retrieved using a unique key, and all related information is returned together, without needing to look up multiple tables.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] A key difference between the document-oriented and relational models is that the data formats are not predefined in the document case.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] In most cases, any sort of document can be stored in a database, and documents can change in type and form over time.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] For example, a new field such as COUNTRY_FLAG can be added to new documents as they are inserted without affecting existing documents.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] To aid retrieval, document-oriented systems generally allow the administrator to provide hints to the database for locating certain types of information.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] These hints work in a similar fashion to indexes in relational databases.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] Many systems also allow additional metadata outside the content of the document itself, such as tagging entries as part of an address book, which enables retrieval of related information, for instance, all the address book entries.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] This provides functionality similar to a table, but separates the concept (categories of data) from its physical implementation (tables).
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] In the traditional normalized relational model, objects in the database are represented as separate rows of data, with no inherent structure beyond what is defined in the tables.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] This can create difficulties when translating programming objects to and from their corresponding database rows, a challenge known as object-relational impedance mismatch.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] In contrast, document stores often map programming objects directly into the database, preserving much of their internal structure.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] Databases using this approach are frequently described as NoSQL systems.
[src:mongoose-odm/document-oriented-database] Most XML databases are document-oriented databases.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] The **`JSON`** namespace object contains static methods for parsing values from and converting values to JavaScript Object Notation (JSON).
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] Unlike most global objects, `JSON` is not a constructor.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] You cannot use it with the `new` operator or invoke the `JSON` object as a function.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] All properties and methods of `JSON` are static (just like the `Math` object).
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] JSON is a syntax for serializing objects, arrays, numbers, strings, booleans, and `null`.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] It is based upon JavaScript syntax, but is distinct from JavaScript: most of JavaScript is *not* JSON.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] Property names must be double-quoted strings; trailing commas are forbidden.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] A decimal point must be followed by at least one digit.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] Any JSON text is a valid JavaScript expression, but only after the JSON superset revision.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] Before the revision, U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR and U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR are allowed in string literals and property keys in JSON; but the same use in JavaScript string literals is a `SyntaxError`.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] Other differences include allowing only double-quoted strings and no support for `undefined` or comments.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] For those who wish to use a more human-friendly configuration format based on JSON, there is JSON5, used by the Babel compiler, and the more commonly used YAML.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] The same text may represent different values in JavaScript object literals vs.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] For more information, see Object literal syntax vs.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] Insignificant whitespace may be present anywhere except within a `JSONNumber` (numbers must contain no whitespace) or `JSONString` (where it is interpreted as the corresponding character in the string, or would cause an error).
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] The tab (U+0009), carriage return (U+000D), line feed (U+000A), and space (U+0020) characters are the only valid whitespace characters.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] The initial value of the `[Symbol.toStringTag]` property is the string `"JSON"`.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] This property is used in `Object.prototype.toString()`.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] Tests whether a value is an object returned by `JSON.rawJSON()`.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] Parse a piece of string text as JSON, optionally transforming the produced value and its properties, and return the value.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] Creates a "raw JSON" object containing a piece of JSON text.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] When serialized to JSON, the raw JSON object is treated as if it is already a piece of JSON.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] Return a JSON string corresponding to the specified value, optionally including only certain properties or replacing property values in a user-defined manner.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] JSON can contain number literals of arbitrary precision.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] However, it is not possible to represent all JSON numbers exactly in JavaScript, because JavaScript uses floating point representation which has a fixed precision.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] This means there is no JavaScript number that corresponds precisely to the `12345678901234567890` JSON number.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] You want to serialize it and then parse to the same exact number.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] There are, in general, two ways to ensure that numbers are losslessly converted to JSON and parsed back: one involves a JSON number, another involves a JSON string.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] JSON is a *communication format*, so if you use JSON, you are likely communicating with another system (HTTP request, storing in database, etc.).
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] The best solution to choose depends on the recipient system.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] If the recipient system does not have same JSON-handling capabilities as JavaScript, and does not support high precision numbers, you may want to serialize the number as a string, and then handle it as a string on the recipient side.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] This is also the only option in older JavaScript.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] To specify how custom data types (including `BigInt`) should be serialized to JSON, either add a `toJSON` method to your data type, or use the `replacer` function of `JSON.stringify()`.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] In either case, the JSON text will look like `{"gross_gdp":"12345678901234567890"}`, where the value is a string, not a number.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] Then, on the recipient side, you can parse the JSON and handle the string.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] If the recipient of this message natively supports high precision numbers (such as Python integers), passing numbers as JSON numbers is obviously better, because they can directly parse to the high precision type instead of parsing a string from JSON, and then parsing a number from the string.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] In JavaScript, you can serialize arbitrary data types to JSON numbers without producing a number value first (resulting in loss of precision) by using `JSON.rawJSON()` to precisely specify what the JSON source text should be.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] The text passed to `JSON.rawJSON` is treated as if it is already a piece of JSON, so it won't be serialized again as a string.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] This JSON can then be parsed by the recipient without any extra processing, provided that the recipient system does not have the same precision limitations as JavaScript.
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] When parsing JSON containing high-precision numbers in JavaScript, take extra care because when `JSON.parse()` invokes the `reviver` function, the value you receive is already parsed (and has lost precision).
[src:mongoose-odm/global-objects-json] You can use the `context.source` parameter of the `JSON.parse()` `reviver` function to re-parse the number yourself.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] If you haven't yet done so, please take a minute to read the quickstart to get an idea of how Mongoose works.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] If you are migrating from 7.x to 8.x please take a moment to read the migration guide.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Everything in Mongoose starts with a Schema.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Each schema maps to a MongoDB collection and defines the shape of the documents within that collection.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] If you want to add additional keys later, use the Schema#add method.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Each key in our code `blogSchema` defines a property in our documents which will be cast to its associated SchemaType.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] For example, we've defined a property `title` which will be cast to the String SchemaType and property `date` which will be cast to a `Date` SchemaType.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Notice above that if a property only requires a type, it can be specified using a shorthand notation (contrast the `title` property above with the `date` property).
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Keys may also be assigned nested objects containing further key/type definitions like the `meta` property above.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] This will happen whenever a key's value is a POJO that doesn't have a `type` property.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] In these cases, Mongoose only creates actual schema paths for leaves in the tree.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] (like `meta.votes` and `meta.favs` above), and the branches do not have actual paths.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] A side-effect of this is that `meta` above cannot have its own validation.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] If validation is needed up the tree, a path needs to be created up the tree - see the Subdocuments section for more information on how to do this.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Also read the Mixed subsection of the SchemaTypes guide for some gotchas.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Schemas not only define the structure of your document and casting of properties, they also define document instance methods, static Model methods, compound indexes, and document lifecycle hooks called middleware.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] To use our schema definition, we need to convert our `blogSchema` into a Model we can work with.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] By default, Mongoose adds an `_id` property to your schemas.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] When you create a new document with the automatically added `_id` property, Mongoose creates a new `_id` of type ObjectId to your document.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] You can also overwrite Mongoose's default `_id` with your own `_id`.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Just be careful: Mongoose will refuse to save a top-level document that doesn't have an `_id`, so you're responsible for setting `_id` if you define your own `_id` path.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Mongoose also adds an `_id` property to subdocuments.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] You can disable the `_id` property on your subdocuments as follows.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Mongoose does allow saving subdocuments without an `_id` property.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Documents have many of their own built-in instance methods.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] We may also define our own custom document instance methods.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Now all of our `animal` instances have a `findSimilarTypes` method available to them.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] You can also add static functions to your model.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Do **not** declare statics using ES6 arrow functions (`=>`).
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Arrow functions explicitly prevent binding `this`, so the above examples will not work because of the value of `this`.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] You can also add query helper functions, which are like instance methods but for mongoose queries.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Query helper methods let you extend mongoose's chainable query builder API.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] With mongoose, we define these indexes within our `Schema` at the path level or the `schema` level.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Defining indexes at the schema level is necessary when creating compound indexes.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] See SchemaType#index() for other index options.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] When your application starts up, Mongoose automatically calls `createIndex` for each defined index in your schema.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Mongoose will call `createIndex` for each index sequentially, and emit an 'index' event on the model when all the `createIndex` calls succeeded or when there was an error.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] While nice for development, it is recommended this behavior be disabled in production since index creation can cause a significant performance impact.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Disable the behavior by setting the `autoIndex` option of your schema to `false`, or globally on the connection by setting the option `autoIndex` to `false`.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Mongoose will emit an `index` event on the model when indexes are done building or an error occurred.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] See also the Model#ensureIndexes method.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Virtuals are document properties that you can get and set but that do not get persisted to MongoDB.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] The getters are useful for formatting or combining fields, while setters are useful for de-composing a single value into multiple values for storage.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Suppose you want to print out the person's full name.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] But concatenating the first and last name every time can get cumbersome.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] And what if you want to do some extra processing on the name, like removing diacritics?
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] A virtual property getter lets you define a `fullName` property that won't get persisted to MongoDB.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] If you use `toJSON()` or `toObject()` Mongoose will *not* include virtuals by default.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Pass `{ virtuals: true }` to `toJSON()` or `toObject()` to include virtuals.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] The above caveat for `toJSON()` also includes the output of calling `JSON.stringify()` on a Mongoose document, because `JSON.stringify()` calls `toJSON()`.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] To include virtuals in `JSON.stringify()` output, you can either call `toObject({ virtuals: true })` on the document before calling `JSON.stringify()`, or set the `toJSON: { virtuals: true }` option on your schema.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] You can also add a custom setter to your virtual that will let you set both first name and last name via the `fullName` virtual.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Virtual property setters are applied before other validation.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] So the example above would still work even if the `first` and `last` name fields were required.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Only non-virtual properties work as part of queries and for field selection.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Since virtuals are not stored in MongoDB, you can't query with them.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Aliases are a particular type of virtual where the getter and setter seamlessly get and set another property.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] This is handy for saving network bandwidth, so you can convert a short property name stored in the database into a longer name for code readability.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] You can also declare aliases on nested paths.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] It is easier to use nested schemas and subdocuments, but you can also declare nested path aliases inline as long as you use the full nested path `nested.myProp` as the alias.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] By default, Mongoose's `init()` function creates all the indexes defined in your model's schema by calling `Model.createIndexes()` after you successfully connect to MongoDB.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Creating indexes automatically is great for development and test environments.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] But index builds can also create significant load on your production database.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] If you want to manage indexes carefully in production, you can set `autoIndex` to false.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] The `autoIndex` option is set to `true` by default.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Before Mongoose builds indexes, it calls `Model.createCollection()` to create the underlying collection in MongoDB by default.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Calling `createCollection()` sets the collection's default collation based on the collation option and establishes the collection as a capped collection if you set the `capped` schema option.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] You can disable this behavior by setting `autoCreate` to `false` using `mongoose.set('autoCreate', false)`.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Like `autoIndex`, `autoCreate` is helpful for development and test environments, but you may want to disable it for production to avoid unnecessary database calls.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Unfortunately, `createCollection()` cannot change an existing collection.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] For example, if you add `capped: { size: 1024 }` to your schema and the existing collection is not capped, `createCollection()` will **not** overwrite the existing collection.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] That is because the MongoDB server does not allow changing a collection's options without dropping the collection first.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] By default, mongoose buffers commands when the connection goes down until the driver manages to reconnect.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] To disable buffering, set `bufferCommands` to false.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] The schema `bufferCommands` option overrides the global `bufferCommands` option.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] If `bufferCommands` is on, this option sets the maximum amount of time Mongoose buffering will wait before throwing an error.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] If not specified, Mongoose will use 10000 (10 seconds).
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Mongoose supports MongoDBs capped collections.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] To specify the underlying MongoDB collection be `capped`, set the `capped` option to the maximum size of the collection in bytes.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] The `capped` option may also be set to an object if you want to pass additional options like max.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] In this case you must explicitly pass the `size` option, which is required.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Mongoose by default produces a collection name by passing the model name to the `utils.toCollectionName` method.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Set this option if you need a different name for your collection.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] When you define a discriminator, Mongoose adds a path to your schema that stores which discriminator a document is an instance of.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] By default, Mongoose adds an `__t` path, but you can set `discriminatorKey` to overwrite this default.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] When `excludeIndexes` is `true`, Mongoose will not create indexes from the given subdocument schema.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] This option only works when the schema is used in a subdocument path or document array path, Mongoose ignores this option if set on the top-level schema for a model.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Mongoose assigns each of your schemas an `id` virtual getter by default which returns the document's `_id` field cast to a string, or in the case of ObjectIds, its hexString.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] If you don't want an `id` getter added to your schema, you may disable it by passing this option at schema construction time.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Mongoose assigns each of your schemas an `_id` field by default if one is not passed into the Schema constructor.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] The type assigned is an ObjectId to coincide with MongoDB's default behavior.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] If you don't want an `_id` added to your schema at all, you may disable it using this option.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] You can **only** use this option on subdocuments.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Mongoose can't save a document without knowing its id, so you will get an error if you try to save a document without an `_id`.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Mongoose will, by default, "minimize" schemas by removing empty objects.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] This behavior can be overridden by setting `minimize` option to `false`.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Allows setting query#read options at the schema level, providing us a way to apply default ReadPreferences to all queries derived from a model.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] The alias of each pref is also permitted so instead of having to type out 'secondaryPreferred' and getting the spelling wrong, we can simply pass 'sp'.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] The read option also allows us to specify *tag sets*.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] These tell the driver from which members of the replica-set it should attempt to read.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Read more about tag sets in the MongoDB documentation on replica set tag sets and in the MongoDB core documentation on read preference.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Allows setting write concern at the schema level.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] The `shardKey` option is used when we have a sharded MongoDB architecture.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Each sharded collection is given a shard key which must be present in all insert/update operations.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] We just need to set this schema option to the same shard key and we’ll be all set.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] The strict option, (enabled by default), ensures that values passed to our model constructor that were not specified in our schema do not get saved to the db.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] This also affects the use of `doc.set()` to set a property value.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] The `strict` option may also be set to `"throw"` which will cause errors to be produced instead of dropping the bad data.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Mongoose supports a separate `strictQuery` option to avoid strict mode for query filters.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] This is because empty query filters cause Mongoose to return all documents in the model, which can cause issues.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] The `strict` option does apply to updates.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] The `strictQuery` option is **just** for query filters.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Mongoose has a separate `strictQuery` option to toggle strict mode for the `filter` parameter to queries.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] In Mongoose 7, `strictQuery` is `false` by default.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Exactly the same as the toObject option but only applies when the document's `toJSON` method is called.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] To see all available `toJSON/toObject` options, read this.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Documents have a toObject method which converts the mongoose document into a plain JavaScript object.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Instead of applying these options on a per-document basis, we may declare the options at the schema level and have them applied to all of the schema's documents by default.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] To see all available `toObject` options, read this.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] By default, if you have an object with key 'type' in your schema, mongoose will interpret it as a type declaration.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] However, for applications like geoJSON, the 'type' property is important.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] If you want to control which key mongoose uses to find type declarations, set the 'typeKey' schema option.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] By default, documents are automatically validated before they are saved to the database.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] This is to prevent saving an invalid document.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] If you want to handle validation manually, and be able to save objects which don't pass validation, you can set `validateBeforeSave` to false.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] The `versionKey` is a property set on each document when first created by Mongoose.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] This keys value contains the internal revision of the document.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] The `versionKey` option is a string that represents the path to use for versioning.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Note that Mongoose's default versioning is **not** a full optimistic concurrency solution.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Mongoose's default versioning only operates on arrays as shown below.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] If you need optimistic concurrency support for `save()`, you can set the `optimisticConcurrency` option.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Document versioning can also be disabled by setting the `versionKey` to `false`.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Mongoose *only* updates the version key when you use `save()`.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] If you use `update()`, `findOneAndUpdate()`, etc.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Mongoose will **not** update the version key.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] As a workaround, you can use the below middleware.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Optimistic concurrency is a strategy to ensure the document you're updating didn't change between when you loaded it using `find()` or `findOne()`, and when you update it using `save()`.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] For example, suppose you have a `House` model that contains a list of `photos`, and a `status` that represents whether this house shows up in searches.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Suppose that a house that has status `'APPROVED'` must have at least two `photos`.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] The `markApproved()` function looks right in isolation, but there might be a potential issue: what if another function removes the house's photos between the `findOne()` call and the `save()` call?
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] If you set the `optimisticConcurrency` option on the `House` model's schema, the above script will throw an error.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] You can also set `optimisticConcurrency` to an array of field names to only use optimistic concurrency when one of those fields is modified.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Note that setting `optimisticConcurrency` to an array of field names **replaces the default array versioning behavior**.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] For example, if you set `optimisticConcurrency: ['status']`, Mongoose will only throw a `VersionError` if `status` is modified concurrently, and will **not** throw a `VersionError` if an array like `photos` is modified concurrently.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] You can also set `optimisticConcurrency` to an object with an `exclude` property to exclude certain fields from optimistic concurrency.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] This enables optimistic concurrency for all fields except the excluded fields, while still replacing default array versioning behavior.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Sets a default collation for every query and aggregation.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Here's a beginner-friendly overview of collations.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] If you set the `timeseries` option on a schema, Mongoose will create a timeseries collection for any model that you create from that schema.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] `skipVersioning` allows excluding paths from versioning (i.e., the internal revision will not be incremented even if these paths are updated).
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] DO NOT do this unless you know what you're doing.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] For subdocuments, include this on the parent document using the fully qualified path.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] The `timestamps` option tells Mongoose to assign `createdAt` and `updatedAt` fields to your schema.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] By default, the names of the fields are `createdAt` and `updatedAt`.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Customize the field names by setting `timestamps.createdAt` and `timestamps.updatedAt`.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] By default, Mongoose uses `new Date()` to get the current time.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] If you want to overwrite the function Mongoose uses to get the current time, you can set the `timestamps.currentTime` option.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Mongoose will call the `timestamps.currentTime` function whenever it needs to get the current time.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Mongoose supports defining global plugins, plugins that apply to all schemas.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Sometimes, you may only want to apply a given plugin to some schemas.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] If you call `plugin()` with a `tags` option, Mongoose will only apply that plugin to schemas that have a matching entry in `pluginTags`.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] By default, Mongoose will automatically `select()` any populated paths for you, unless you explicitly exclude them.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] To opt out of selecting populated fields by default, set `selectPopulatedPaths` to `false` in your schema.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] For legacy reasons, when there is a validation error in subpath of a single nested schema, Mongoose will record that there was a validation error in the single nested schema path as well.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Set the `storeSubdocValidationError` to `false` on the child schema to make Mongoose only reports the parent error.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Options like `collation` and `capped` affect the options Mongoose passes to MongoDB when creating a new collection.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Mongoose schemas support most MongoDB `createCollection()` options, but not all.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] You can use the `collectionOptions` option to set any `createCollection()` options; Mongoose will use `collectionOptions` as the default values when calling `createCollection()` for your schema.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Similar to `autoIndex`, except for automatically creates any Atlas search indexes defined in your schema.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Unlike `autoIndex`, this option defaults to false.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Read concerns are similar to `writeConcern`, but for read operations like `find()` and `findOne()`.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] To set a default `readConcern`, pass the `readConcern` option to the schema constructor as follows.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Schemas are also pluggable which allows us to package up reusable features into plugins that can be shared with the community or just between your projects.
[src:mongoose-odm/guide] Now that we've covered `Schemas`, let's take a look at SchemaTypes.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] The American software company 10gen began developing MongoDB in 2007 as a component of a planned platform-as-a-service product.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] In 2009, the company shifted to an open-source development model and began offering commercial support and other services.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] In 2013, 10gen changed its name to MongoDB Inc.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] On October 20, 2017, MongoDB became a publicly traded company, listed on NASDAQ as MDB with an IPO price of $24 per share.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] On November 8, 2018, with the stable release 4.0.4, the software's license changed from AGPL 3.0 to SSPL.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] On October 30, 2019, MongoDB teamed with Alibaba Cloud to offer Alibaba Cloud customers a MongoDB-as-a-service solution.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] Customers can use the managed offering from Alibaba's global data centers.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] In December 2025, a major exploit was discovered and titled as "MongoBleed".
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] This exploit led to the compromise of many corporate servers.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] As of May 2025, MongoDB was the fifth most popular database software.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] It focuses mostly on managing large databases of unstructured, "messy" data.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] It's typically used for mobile and web apps that commonly use unstructured databases.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] As of 2024, there were 50,000 MongoDB customers.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] MongoDB was originally best known as a NoSQL database product.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] The company released a database as-a-service product called Atlas in 2016 that became 70 percent of MongoDB's revenue by 2024.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] Over time, MongoDB added analytics, transactional databases, encryption, vector databases, ACID, migration features, and other enterprise tools.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] Initially, the MongoDB software was free and open source under the AGPL license.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] MongoDB adopted an SSPL (server side public license) for future releases starting in 2018.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] MongoDB implements its own query language called *Mongo Query Language* (MQL).
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] MongoDB supports field, range query and regular-expression searches.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] Queries can return specific fields of documents and also include user-defined JavaScript functions.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] Queries can also be configured to return a random sample of results of a given size.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] Fields in a MongoDB document can be indexed with primary and secondary indices.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] MongoDB provides high availability with replica sets.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] A replica set consists of two or more copies of the data.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] Each replica-set member may act in the role of primary or secondary replica at any time.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] All writes and reads are done on the primary replica by default.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] Secondary replicas maintain a copy of the data of the primary using built-in replication.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] When a primary replica fails, the replica set automatically conducts an election process to determine which secondary should become the primary.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] Secondaries can optionally serve read operations, but that data is only eventually consistent by default.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] If the replicated MongoDB deployment only has a single secondary member, a separate daemon called an arbiter must be added to the set.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] It has the single responsibility of resolving the election of the new primary.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] As a consequence, an ideal distributed MongoDB deployment requires at least three separate servers, even in the case of just one primary and one secondary.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] MongoDB scales horizontally using sharding.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] The user chooses a shard key, which determines how the data in a collection will be distributed.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] The data is split into ranges (based on the shard key) and distributed across multiple shards, which are masters with one or more replicas.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] Alternatively, the shard key can be hashed to map to a shard – enabling an even data distribution.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] MongoDB can run over multiple servers, balancing the load or duplicating data to keep the system functional in case of hardware failure.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] MongoDB can be used as a file system, called GridFS, with load-balancing and data-replication features over multiple machines for storing files.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] This function, called a grid file system, is included with MongoDB drivers.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] MongoDB exposes functions for file manipulation and content to developers.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] GridFS can be accessed using the mongofiles utility or plugins for Nginx and lighttpd.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] GridFS divides a file into parts, or chunks, and stores each of those chunks as a separate document.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] MongoDB provides three ways to perform aggregation: the aggregation pipeline (preferred), the map-reduce function (deprecated as of MongoDB 5.0) and single-purpose aggregation methods.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] Map-reduce can be used for batch processing of data and aggregation operations.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] However, according to MongoDB's documentation, the aggregation pipeline provides better performance for most aggregation operations.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] The aggregation framework enables users to obtain results similar to those returned by queries that include the SQL GROUP BY clause.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] Aggregation operators can be strung together to form a pipeline, analogous to Unix pipes.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] The aggregation framework includes the $lookup operator, which can join documents from multiple collections, as well as statistical operators such as standard deviation.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] MongoDB supports fixed-size collections called capped collections.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] This type of collection maintains insertion order and, once the specified size has been reached, behaves like a circular queue.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] MongoDB supports multi-document ACID transactions since the 4.0 release in June 2018.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] As of October 2018, MongoDB is released under the Server Side Public License (SSPL), a non-free license developed by the project.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] It replaces the GNU Affero General Public License.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] In contrast to the AGPL, the SSPL prevents anyone but MongoDB Inc. from making MongoDB "available as a service" without negotiating a separate license from MongoDb Inc.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] The license text specifies a condition for making MongoDB which MongoDB Inc. has claimed to be similar to AGPL, but is actually impossible to comply with.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] The condition states that "all programs that you use to make the Program" ...
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] "available as a service" must be published under the SSPL.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] However, a core component of MongoDB called WiredTiger is licensed as GPL, and the GPL does not allow redistribution under any license except the GPL.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] This does not apply to the copyright holder (MongoDB Inc.).
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] Since MongoDB's SSPL adoption in 2018, no one has ever provided MongoDB as a paid service under the SSPL license (including MongoDB Inc.).
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] The SSPL was submitted for certification to the Open Source Initiative but later withdrawn.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] In January 2021, the Open Source Initiative stated that SSPL is not an open source license.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] The language drivers are available under an Apache License.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] In addition, MongoDB Inc. offers proprietary licenses for MongoDB.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] The last versions licensed as AGPL version 3 are 4.0.3 (stable) and 4.1.4.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] MongoDB has been removed from the Debian, Fedora and Red Hat Enterprise Linux distributions because of the licensing change.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] Fedora determined that the SSPL version 1 is not a free software license because it is "intentionally crafted to be aggressively discriminatory" towards commercial users.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] Because of MongoDB's default security configuration, which allows any user full access to the database, data from tens of thousands of MongoDB installations has been stolen.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] Furthermore, many MongoDB servers have been held for ransom.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] In September 2017, Davi Ottenheimer head of product security at MongoDB, proclaimed that measures had been taken to defend against these risks.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] In some failure scenarios in which an application can access two distinct MongoDB processes that cannot access each other, it is possible for MongoDB to return stale reads.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] It is also possible for MongoDB to roll back writes that have been acknowledged.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] The issue was addressed in version 3.4.0, released in November 2016, and applied to earlier releases from v3.2.12 onward.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] Before version 2.2, locks were implemented on a per-server-process basis.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] With version 2.2, locks were implemented at the database level.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] Beginning with version 3.0, pluggable storage engines are available, and each storage engine may implement locks differently.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] With MongoDB 3.0, locks are implemented at the collection level for the MMAPv1 storage engine, while the WiredTiger storage engine uses an optimistic concurrency protocol that effectively provides document-level locking.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] Even with versions prior to 3.0, one approach to increase concurrency is to use sharding.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] In some situations, reads and writes will yield their locks.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] If MongoDB predicts that a page is unlikely to be in memory, operations will yield their lock while the pages load.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] The use of lock yielding expanded greatly in version 2.2.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] Until version 3.3.11, MongoDB could not perform collation-based sorting and was limited to bytewise comparison via memcmp, which would not provide correct ordering for many non-English languages when used with a Unicode encoding.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] Prior to MongoDB 4.0, queries against an index were not atomic.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] Documents that were updated while queries was running could be missed.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] The introduction of the snapshot read concern in MongoDB 4.0 eliminated this risk.
[src:mongoose-odm/mongodb] FerretDB is an open source project that converts MongoDB 5.0 wire protocol queries into SQL, allowing clients to query postgreSQL (or other databases) using the Mongo wire protocol.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] An **object database** or **object-oriented database** is a database management system in which information is represented in the form of objects as used in object-oriented programming.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] Object databases are different from relational databases which are table-oriented.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] A third type, object–relational databases, is a hybrid of both approaches.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] Object databases have been considered since the early 1980s.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] Object-oriented database management systems (OODBMSs) also called ODBMS (Object Database Management System) combine database capabilities with object-oriented programming language capabilities.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] OODBMSs allow object-oriented programmers to develop the product, store them as objects, and replicate or modify existing objects to make new objects within the OODBMS.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] Because the database is integrated with the programming language, the programmer can maintain consistency within one environment, in that both the OODBMS and the programming language will use the same model of representation.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] Relational DBMS projects, by way of contrast, maintain a clearer division between the database model and the application.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] As the usage of web-based technology increases with the implementation of Intranets and extranets, companies have a vested interest in OODBMSs to display their complex data.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] Using a DBMS that has been specifically designed to store data as objects gives an advantage to those companies that are geared towards multimedia presentation or organizations that utilize computer-aided design (CAD).
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] Some object-oriented databases are designed to work well with object-oriented programming languages such as Delphi, Ruby, Python, JavaScript, Perl, Java, C#, Visual Basic .NET, C++, Objective-C and Smalltalk; others such as JADE have their own programming languages.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] OODBMSs use exactly the same model as object-oriented programming languages.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] Object database management systems grew out of research during the early to mid-1970s into having intrinsic database management support for graph-structured objects.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] The term "object-oriented database system" first appeared around 1985.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] Notable research projects included Encore-Ob/Server (Brown University), EXODUS (University of Wisconsin–Madison), IRIS (Hewlett-Packard), ODE (Bell Labs), ORION (Microelectronics and Computer Technology Corporation or MCC), Vodak (GMD-IPSI), and Zeitgeist (Texas Instruments).
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] The ORION project had more published papers than any of the other efforts.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] Won Kim of MCC compiled the best of those papers in a book published by The MIT Press.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] Early commercial products included Gemstone (Servio Logic, name changed to GemStone Systems), Gbase (Graphael), and Vbase (Ontologic).
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] Additional commercial products entered the market in the late 1980s through the mid 1990s.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] Some of these products remain on the market and have been joined by new open source and commercial products such as InterSystems Caché.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] Object database management systems added the concept of persistence to object programming languages.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] The early commercial products were integrated with various languages: GemStone (Smalltalk), Gbase (LISP), Vbase (COP) and VOSS (Virtual Object Storage System for Smalltalk).
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] For much of the 1990s, C++ dominated the commercial object database management market.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] Vendors added Java in the late 1990s and more recently, C#.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] Object databases based on persistent programming acquired a niche in application areas such as engineering and spatial databases, telecommunications, and scientific areas such as high energy physics and molecular biology.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] Another group of object databases focuses on embedded use in devices, packaged software, and real-time systems.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] Most object databases also offer some kind of query language, allowing objects to be found using a declarative programming approach.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] It is in the area of object query languages, and the integration of the query and navigational interfaces, that the biggest differences between products are found.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] An attempt at standardization was made by the ODMG with the Object Query Language, OQL.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] Access to data can be faster because an object can be retrieved directly without a search, by following pointers.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] Another area of variation between products is in the way that the schema of a database is defined.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] A general characteristic, however, is that the programming language and the database schema use the same type definitions.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] Multimedia applications are facilitated because the class methods associated with the data are responsible for its correct interpretation.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] Many object databases, for example Gemstone or VOSS, offer support for versioning.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] An object can be viewed as the set of all its versions.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] Also, object versions can be treated as objects in their own right.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] Some object databases also provide systematic support for triggers and constraints which are the basis of active databases.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] The efficiency of such a database is also greatly improved in areas which demand massive amounts of data about one item.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] For example, a banking institution could get the user's account information and provide them efficiently with extensive information such as transactions, account information entries etc.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] The Object Data Management Group was a consortium of object database and object–relational mapping vendors, members of the academic community, and interested parties.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] Its goal was to create a set of specifications that would allow for portable applications that store objects in database management systems.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] It published several versions of its specification.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] By 2001, most of the major object database and object–relational mapping vendors claimed conformance to the ODMG Java Language Binding.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] Compliance to the other components of the specification was mixed.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] In 2001, the ODMG Java Language Binding was submitted to the Java Community Process as a basis for the Java Data Objects specification.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] The ODMG member companies then decided to concentrate their efforts on the Java Data Objects specification.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] As a result, the ODMG disbanded in 2001.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] Many object database ideas were also absorbed into SQL:1999 and have been implemented in varying degrees in object–relational database products.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] In 2005 Cook, Rai, and Rosenberger proposed to drop all standardization efforts to introduce additional object-oriented query APIs but rather use the OO programming language itself, i.e., Java and .NET, to express queries.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] Similarly, Microsoft announced Language Integrated Query (LINQ) and DLINQ, an implementation of LINQ, in September 2005, to provide close, language-integrated database query capabilities with its programming languages C# and VB.NET 9.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] In February 2006, the Object Management Group (OMG) announced that they had been granted the right to develop new specifications based on the ODMG 3.0 specification and the formation of the Object Database Technology Working Group (ODBT WG).
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] The work of the ODBT WG was suspended in March 2009 when, subsequent to the economic turmoil in late 2008, the ODB vendors involved in this effort decided to focus their resources elsewhere.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] In January 2007 the World Wide Web Consortium gave final recommendation status to the XQuery language.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] Some of the ideas developed originally for object databases found their way into XQuery, but XQuery is not intrinsically object-oriented.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] Because of the popularity of XML, XQuery engines compete with object databases as a vehicle for storage of data that is too complex or variable to hold conveniently in a relational database.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] XQuery also allows modules to be written to provide encapsulation features that have been provided by Object-Oriented systems.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] XQuery v1 and XPath v2 and later are powerful and are available in both open source and libre (FOSS) software, as well as in commercial systems.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] They are easy to learn and use, and very powerful and fast.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] They are not relational and XQuery is not based on SQL (although one of the people who designed XQuery also co-invented SQL).
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] But they are also not object-oriented, in the programming sense: XQuery does not use encapsulation with hiding, implicit dispatch, and classes and methods.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] XQuery databases generally use XML and JSON as an interchange format, although other formats are used.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] Since the early 2000s JSON has gained community adoption and popularity in applications where developers are in control of the data format.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] JSONiq, a query-analog of XQuery for JSON (sharing XQuery's core expressions and operations), demonstrated the functional equivalence of the JSON and XML formats for data-oriented information.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] In this context, the main strategy of OODBMS maintainers was to retrofit JSON to their databases (by using it as the internal data type).
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] In January 2016, with the PostgreSQL 9.5 release was the first FOSS OODBMS to offer an efficient JSON internal datatype (JSONB) with a complete set of functions and operations, for all basic relational and non-relational manipulations.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] An object database stores complex data and relationships between data directly, without mapping to relational rows and columns, and this makes them suitable for applications dealing with very complex data.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] Objects have a many-to-many relationship and are accessed by the use of pointers.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] Pointers are linked to objects to establish relationships.
[src:mongoose-odm/object-database] Another benefit of an OODBMS is that it can be programmed with small procedural differences without affecting the entire system.
